# Performance Optimization: Virtualization, Caching, and Profiling Your OpenMaui App

*Master performance optimization techniques to achieve sub-20ms frame times and smooth 60 FPS animations in your Linux desktop applications.*

## Introduction to Performance Metrics

Performance optimization in OpenMaui Linux applications requires understanding the unique characteristics of the SkiaSharp rendering pipeline and the GTK event loop model. Unlike native widget toolkits, OpenMaui renders all UI controls using SkiaSharp's 2D graphics API, which provides incredible flexibility but demands careful attention to performance.

## The 60 FPS Target

Smooth animations require maintaining 60 frames per second, which translates to a **16.67ms budget per frame**. This budget must accommodate:

- Layout calculations and measure/arrange passes
- Skia canvas drawing operations
- GPU command buffer submission (or CPU rasterization in software mode)
- Event handling and gesture recognition
- Data binding updates and property change notifications

The OpenMaui rendering engine uses a sophisticated dirty region tracking system via `DirtyRectManager` to minimize redraws:

```csharp
// Only invalidated regions are redrawn
public void InvalidateRect(SKRect rect)
{
    _dirtyRects.Add(rect);
    RequestRender();
}
```

## Key Performance Indicators

When profiling your OpenMaui app, focus on these critical metrics:

1. **Frame time**: Total time from event loop tick to frame presentation (target: <16.67ms)
2. **Layout time**: Time spent in measure/arrange cycles (target: <2ms)
3. **Render time**: SkiaSharp drawing operations (target: <8ms)
4. **GC pressure**: Allocations per frame (target: <1KB for steady state)
5. **Memory footprint**: Total managed heap size and native resource usage

The `SkiaRenderingEngine` provides built-in performance tracking:

```csharp
public class SkiaRenderingEngine
{
    private Stopwatch _frameTimer = new();

    public void RenderFrame(SKCanvas canvas)
    {
        _frameTimer.Restart();

        // Render only dirty regions
        foreach (var dirtyRect in _dirtyRects)
        {
            canvas.Save();
            canvas.ClipRect(dirtyRect);
            RenderRegion(canvas, dirtyRect);
            canvas.Restore();
        }

        _frameTimer.Stop();
        if (_frameTimer.ElapsedMilliseconds > 16)
        {
            Debug.WriteLine($"Frame time exceeded budget: {_frameTimer.ElapsedMilliseconds}ms");
        }
    }
}
```

## Understanding the Threading Model

OpenMaui uses GTK's single-threaded event loop model with dispatcher-based marshaling. All UI operations must occur on the main thread:

```csharp
// Always marshal to UI thread for property updates
Dispatcher.Dispatch(() =>
{
    MyLabel.Text = "Updated from background thread";
});
```

Blocking the UI thread for more than 16ms will cause dropped frames and janky animations. Offload expensive operations to background threads using `Task.Run()` and marshal results back to the UI thread.

## View Virtualization for CollectionView and CarouselView

View virtualization is the cornerstone of performance optimization for scrollable collections. The `SkiaCollectionView` and `SkiaCarouselView` implementations inherit from `SkiaItemsView`, which provides sophisticated view recycling to handle thousands of items efficiently.

## How View Recycling Works

Instead of creating view instances for every item in your data source, virtualization maintains a small pool of reusable views—only enough to fill the visible viewport plus a small buffer:

```csharp
public class SkiaItemsView : SkiaLayoutView
{
    private readonly List<SkiaView> _recycledViews = new();
    private readonly Dictionary<object, SkiaView> _activeViews = new();

    protected virtual void UpdateVisibleItems()
    {
        var visibleBounds = GetVisibleBounds();
        var visibleItems = GetItemsInBounds(visibleBounds);

        // Recycle views that scrolled out of viewport
        foreach (var kvp in _activeViews.ToList())
        {
            if (!visibleItems.Contains(kvp.Key))
            {
                RecycleView(kvp.Value);
                _activeViews.Remove(kvp.Key);
            }
        }

        // Create or reuse views for visible items
        foreach (var item in visibleItems)
        {
            if (!_activeViews.ContainsKey(item))
            {
                var view = GetOrCreateView();
                view.BindingContext = item;
                _activeViews[item] = view;
            }
        }
    }

    private SkiaView GetOrCreateView()
    {
        if (_recycledViews.Count > 0)
        {
            var view = _recycledViews[0];
            _recycledViews.RemoveAt(0);
            return view;
        }

        return CreateItemView();
    }
}
```

## Optimizing ItemTemplate Performance

The DataTemplate you provide for items has a massive impact on scrolling performance. Follow these guidelines:

### ✅ DO: Use Simple Layouts

```xml
<CollectionView ItemsSource="{Binding Products}">
    <CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
        <DataTemplate>
            <Grid ColumnDefinitions="Auto,*" Padding="8">
                <Image Grid.Column="0" 
                       Source="{Binding ThumbnailUrl}"
                       WidthRequest="48" 
                       HeightRequest="48"/>
                <StackLayout Grid.Column="1" Spacing="4">
                    <Label Text="{Binding Name}" FontSize="14" FontAttributes="Bold"/>
                    <Label Text="{Binding Price, StringFormat='{0:C}'}" FontSize="12"/>
                </StackLayout>
            </Grid>
        </DataTemplate>
    </CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
</CollectionView>
```

### ❌ DON'T: Nest Multiple Layouts

```xml
<!-- This creates excessive layout passes -->
<DataTemplate>
    <Frame>
        <StackLayout>
            <Grid>
                <StackLayout>
                    <!-- Deeply nested layouts hurt performance -->
                </StackLayout>
            </Grid>
        </StackLayout>
    </Frame>
</DataTemplate>
```

## Measuring Item Layout Performance

For complex item templates, measure the layout time to ensure it stays under budget:

```csharp
public class ProductItemView : SkiaContentView
{
    protected override Size MeasureOverride(double widthConstraint, double heightConstraint)
    {
        var sw = Stopwatch.StartNew();
        var result = base.MeasureOverride(widthConstraint, heightConstraint);
        sw.Stop();

        if (sw.ElapsedMilliseconds > 1)
        {
            Debug.WriteLine($"Item measure took {sw.ElapsedMilliseconds}ms - consider simplifying");
        }

        return result;
    }
}
```

## CarouselView Optimization

`SkiaCarouselView` uses horizontal virtualization with snap-to-item behavior. Enable loop mode carefully—it requires maintaining additional buffered views:

```csharp
// Disable loop mode for better performance with large datasets
<CarouselView ItemsSource="{Binding Images}" 
              Loop="False"
              PeekAreaInsets="20">
    <CarouselView.ItemTemplate>
        <DataTemplate>
            <Image Source="{Binding Url}" Aspect="AspectFill"/>
        </DataTemplate>
    </CarouselView.ItemTemplate>
</CarouselView>
```

## Performance Budget for Collections

For optimal scrolling performance:

- **Item measure time**: <1ms per item
- **Item render time**: <2ms per item
- **Scroll event handling**: <5ms total
- **View recycling overhead**: <0.5ms per recycle

With these targets, you can maintain 60 FPS even during fast scrolling through thousands of items.

## Render Caching Strategies

OpenMaui's rendering engine includes sophisticated caching mechanisms to avoid redundant drawing operations. The `RenderCache` and `TextRenderCache` classes provide automatic caching for expensive rendering operations.

## Understanding Render Caching

Every `SkiaView` can cache its rendered output as a bitmap, eliminating the need to redraw static content every frame:

```csharp
public abstract class SkiaView : IView
{
    private SKBitmap? _renderCache;
    private bool _cacheValid = false;

    public bool EnableRenderCache { get; set; } = false;

    public virtual void Draw(SKCanvas canvas)
    {
        if (EnableRenderCache && _cacheValid && _renderCache != null)
        {
            canvas.DrawBitmap(_renderCache, 0, 0);
            return;
        }

        if (EnableRenderCache)
        {
            // Render to offscreen surface for caching
            var info = new SKImageInfo((int)Width, (int)Height);
            _renderCache?.Dispose();
            _renderCache = new SKBitmap(info);

            using var cacheCanvas = new SKCanvas(_renderCache);
            DrawCore(cacheCanvas);
            _cacheValid = true;

            canvas.DrawBitmap(_renderCache, 0, 0);
        }
        else
        {
            DrawCore(canvas);
        }
    }

    protected void InvalidateCache()
    {
        _cacheValid = false;
    }
}
```

## When to Enable Render Caching

Render caching is beneficial for:

1. **Complex static graphics**: Charts, diagrams, or decorative elements that don't change frequently
2. **Text-heavy layouts**: Labels with complex formatted strings and font fallback
3. **SVG images**: Vector graphics that require expensive path rendering
4. **Shadowed or blurred elements**: Effects with high computational cost

### Example: Caching a Complex Dashboard Card

```csharp
public class DashboardCard : SkiaFrame
{
    public DashboardCard()
    {
        // Enable caching for this complex card
        EnableRenderCache = true;

        Content = new SkiaGrid
        {
            RowDefinitions = 
            {
                new RowDefinition { Height = GridLength.Auto },
                new RowDefinition { Height = GridLength.Star }
            },
            Children =
            {
                new SkiaLabel { Text = "Sales Overview", FontSize = 18, FontAttributes = FontAttributes.Bold },
                new ChartView { Data = salesData }.Row(1)
            }
        };
    }

    public void UpdateData(SalesData newData)
    {
        // Invalidate cache when data changes
        InvalidateCache();
        ((ChartView)((SkiaGrid)Content).Children[1]).Data = newData;
    }
}
```

## Text Render Caching

Text rendering is particularly expensive due to font shaping with HarfBuzzSharp and emoji/CJK fallback. The `TextRenderCache` provides automatic caching:

```csharp
public class TextRenderCache
{
    private readonly Dictionary<string, SKTextBlob> _cache = new();
    private const int MaxCacheSize = 1000;

    public SKTextBlob GetOrCreate(string text, SKFont font)
    {
        var key = $"{text}_{font.Typeface.FamilyName}_{font.Size}";

        if (_cache.TryGetValue(key, out var blob))
        {
            return blob;
        }

        // Expensive: Shape text with HarfBuzz
        blob = ShapeText(text, font);

        if (_cache.Count >= MaxCacheSize)
        {
            // Evict oldest entry (simplified LRU)
            var oldestKey = _cache.Keys.First();
            _cache[oldestKey].Dispose();
            _cache.Remove(oldestKey);
        }

        _cache[key] = blob;
        return blob;
    }
}
```

## Image Caching

`SkiaImage` automatically caches decoded bitmaps to avoid repeated decoding:

```csharp
public class SkiaImage : SkiaView
{
    private static readonly Dictionary<string, SKBitmap> _imageCache = new();
    private static long _totalCacheBytes = 0;
    private const long MaxCacheBytes = 100 * 1024 * 1024; // 100MB

    protected override void OnSourceChanged()
    {
        if (Source is UriImageSource uriSource)
        {
            var url = uriSource.Uri.ToString();

            if (_imageCache.TryGetValue(url, out var cached))
            {
                _bitmap = cached;
                InvalidateMeasure();
                return;
            }

            Task.Run(async () =>
            {
                var bitmap = await LoadImageAsync(url);
                var bytes = bitmap.ByteCount;

                // Evict if cache is full
                while (_totalCacheBytes + bytes > MaxCacheBytes && _imageCache.Count > 0)
                {
                    var evictKey = _imageCache.Keys.First();
                    var evictBitmap = _imageCache[evictKey];
                    _totalCacheBytes -= evictBitmap.ByteCount;
                    evictBitmap.Dispose();
                    _imageCache.Remove(evictKey);
                }

                _imageCache[url] = bitmap;
                _totalCacheBytes += bytes;

                Dispatcher.Dispatch(() =>
                {
                    _bitmap = bitmap;
                    InvalidateMeasure();
                });
            });
        }
    }
}
```

## Cache Invalidation Strategies

Proper cache invalidation is critical:

```csharp
// Invalidate on property changes
protected override void OnPropertyChanged(string propertyName)
{
    base.OnPropertyChanged(propertyName);

    if (propertyName == nameof(BackgroundColor) || 
        propertyName == nameof(BorderColor) ||
        propertyName == nameof(CornerRadius))
    {
        InvalidateCache();
    }
}
```

## Performance Impact

Properly configured render caching can reduce frame time by 40-60% for complex layouts:

- **Without caching**: 12ms frame time for 20 complex cards
- **With caching**: 5ms frame time (2ms for cache lookup + 3ms for compositing)
- **Memory cost**: ~2-4MB per cached view at 1920x1080

Monitor memory usage carefully—excessive caching can lead to out-of-memory conditions on systems with limited RAM.

## Gesture Manager Performance

OpenMaui's gesture recognition system processes pointer events (mouse and touch) to detect taps, pans, swipes, and pinches. Inefficient gesture handling can significantly impact responsiveness and frame rates.

## The Gesture Recognition Pipeline

Gesture recognition occurs in multiple stages:

1. **Native event capture**: X11/Wayland pointer events
2. **Event translation**: Convert to platform-agnostic coordinates
3. **Hit testing**: Determine which view(s) should receive the event
4. **Gesture recognition**: Match event sequences to gesture patterns
5. **Event dispatch**: Invoke gesture handlers

```csharp
public class GestureManager
{
    private readonly List<GestureRecognizer> _recognizers = new();
    private readonly Dictionary<int, PointerState> _activePointers = new();

    public void ProcessPointerEvent(PointerEvent evt)
    {
        var sw = Stopwatch.StartNew();

        // Update pointer state
        _activePointers[evt.PointerId] = new PointerState
        {
            Position = evt.Position,
            Timestamp = evt.Timestamp
        };

        // Perform hit testing
        var hitViews = HitTest(evt.Position);

        // Process each recognizer
        foreach (var recognizer in _recognizers)
        {
            if (recognizer.CanRecognize(evt, _activePointers))
            {
                recognizer.ProcessEvent(evt, hitViews);
            }
        }

        sw.Stop();
        if (sw.ElapsedMilliseconds > 2)
        {
            Debug.WriteLine($"Gesture processing took {sw.ElapsedMilliseconds}ms - optimize hit testing");
        }
    }
}
```

## Optimizing Hit Testing

Hit testing determines which views should receive pointer events. Naive implementations test every view in the tree:

```csharp
// ❌ SLOW: Tests every view
private List<SkiaView> HitTestSlow(Point point)
{
    var results = new List<SkiaView>();

    foreach (var view in _allViews)
    {
        if (view.Bounds.Contains(point) && view.IsEnabled)
        {
            results.Add(view);
        }
    }

    return results;
}

// ✅ FAST: Uses spatial indexing
private List<SkiaView> HitTestFast(Point point)
{
    var results = new List<SkiaView>();

    // Use quad-tree for O(log n) lookup
    var candidates = _spatialIndex.Query(point);

    foreach (var view in candidates)
    {
        if (view.Bounds.Contains(point) && view.IsEnabled)
        {
            results.Add(view);
        }
    }

    return results;
}
```

## Gesture Recognizer Performance

Each gesture recognizer should process events in <0.5ms:

```csharp
public class TapGestureRecognizer : GestureRecognizer
{
    private Point _pressPosition;
    private DateTime _pressTime;
    private const double MaxTapDistance = 10; // pixels
    private const int MaxTapDuration = 500; // milliseconds

    public override void ProcessEvent(PointerEvent evt, List<SkiaView> hitViews)
    {
        switch (evt.Type)
        {
            case PointerEventType.Pressed:
                _pressPosition = evt.Position;
                _pressTime = DateTime.Now;
                break;

            case PointerEventType.Released:
                var distance = Point.Distance(_pressPosition, evt.Position);
                var duration = (DateTime.Now - _pressTime).TotalMilliseconds;

                if (distance < MaxTapDistance && duration < MaxTapDuration)
                {
                    // Valid tap - invoke handlers
                    foreach (var view in hitViews)
                    {
                        if (view.GestureRecognizers.OfType<TapGestureRecognizer>().Any())
                        {
                            InvokeTapped(view, evt.Position);
                        }
                    }
                }
                break;
        }
    }
}
```

## Reducing Gesture Handler Overhead

Avoid attaching gesture recognizers to every view in a collection:

```xml
<!-- ❌ BAD: Creates 1000 gesture recognizers -->
<CollectionView ItemsSource="{Binding Items}">
    <CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
        <DataTemplate>
            <Frame>
                <Frame.GestureRecognizers>
                    <TapGestureRecognizer Command="{Binding TapCommand}"/>
                </Frame.GestureRecognizers>
                <Label Text="{Binding Name}"/>
            </Frame>
        </DataTemplate>
    </CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
</CollectionView>

<!-- ✅ GOOD: Use SelectionMode instead -->
<CollectionView ItemsSource="{Binding Items}"
                SelectionMode="Single"
                SelectionChanged="OnItemSelected">
    <CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
        <DataTemplate>
            <Frame>
                <Label Text="{Binding Name}"/>
            </Frame>
        </DataTemplate>
    </CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
</CollectionView>
```

## Pan Gesture Optimization

Pan gestures fire continuously during movement. Throttle updates to avoid overwhelming the UI thread:

```csharp
public class OptimizedPanGestureRecognizer : PanGestureRecognizer
{
    private DateTime _lastUpdate = DateTime.MinValue;
    private const int ThrottleMs = 16; // ~60 FPS

    protected override void OnPanUpdated(PanUpdatedEventArgs e)
    {
        var now = DateTime.Now;

        if ((now - _lastUpdate).TotalMilliseconds < ThrottleMs)
        {
            return; // Skip this update
        }

        _lastUpdate = now;
        base.OnPanUpdated(e);
    }
}
```

## Gesture Performance Budget

Target performance for gesture processing:

- **Hit testing**: <0.5ms per event
- **Gesture recognition**: <0.5ms per recognizer
- **Event dispatch**: <1ms total
- **Total gesture overhead**: <2ms per pointer event

With these targets, gesture handling consumes only 12% of your frame budget, leaving ample time for rendering and layout.

## Memory Management and Disposal Patterns

Proper memory management is critical for long-running desktop applications. OpenMaui applications must carefully manage both managed (.NET) and native (SkiaSharp, GTK) resources to avoid memory leaks and degraded performance.

## The IDisposable Pattern

All `SkiaView` implementations should properly dispose of native resources:

```csharp
public abstract class SkiaView : IView, IDisposable
{
    private SKPaint? _backgroundPaint;
    private SKBitmap? _renderCache;
    private bool _disposed = false;

    protected virtual void Dispose(bool disposing)
    {
        if (_disposed)
            return;

        if (disposing)
        {
            // Dispose managed resources
            foreach (var child in Children)
            {
                (child as IDisposable)?.Dispose();
            }
        }

        // Dispose native resources
        _backgroundPaint?.Dispose();
        _backgroundPaint = null;

        _renderCache?.Dispose();
        _renderCache = null;

        _disposed = true;
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Dispose(true);
        GC.SuppressFinalize(this);
    }

    ~SkiaView()
    {
        Dispose(false);
    }
}
```

## Event Handler Leaks

Event handlers are a common source of memory leaks. Always unsubscribe when views are removed:

```csharp
public class ProductListView : SkiaContentView
{
    private readonly ProductService _productService;

    public ProductListView(ProductService productService)
    {
        _productService = productService;

        // ❌ BAD: Creates strong reference that prevents GC
        _productService.ProductUpdated += OnProductUpdated;
    }

    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing)
    {
        if (disposing)
        {
            // ✅ GOOD: Unsubscribe to allow GC
            _productService.ProductUpdated -= OnProductUpdated;
        }

        base.Dispose(disposing);
    }

    private void OnProductUpdated(object? sender, ProductEventArgs e)
    {
        // Update UI
    }
}
```

## Weak Event Pattern

For long-lived services, use weak event patterns to prevent leaks:

```csharp
public class WeakEventManager<TEventArgs> where TEventArgs : EventArgs
{
    private readonly List<WeakReference<EventHandler<TEventArgs>>> _handlers = new();

    public void AddHandler(EventHandler<TEventArgs> handler)
    {
        _handlers.Add(new WeakReference<EventHandler<TEventArgs>>(handler));
    }

    public void RemoveHandler(EventHandler<TEventArgs> handler)
    {
        _handlers.RemoveAll(wr => 
        {
            if (!wr.TryGetTarget(out var target))
                return true; // Remove dead references

            return target == handler;
        });
    }

    public void RaiseEvent(object sender, TEventArgs args)
    {
        var deadReferences = new List<WeakReference<EventHandler<TEventArgs>>>();

        foreach (var weakRef in _handlers)
        {
            if (weakRef.TryGetTarget(out var handler))
            {
                handler(sender, args);
            }
            else
            {
                deadReferences.Add(weakRef);
            }
        }

        // Clean up dead references
        foreach (var deadRef in deadReferences)
        {
            _handlers.Remove(deadRef);
        }
    }
}
```

## SKPaint Reuse

Creating `SKPaint` objects is expensive. Reuse them across draw calls:

```csharp
public class SkiaButton : SkiaView
{
    private SKPaint? _backgroundPaint;
    private SKPaint? _textPaint;

    protected override void DrawCore(SKCanvas canvas)
    {
        // ❌ BAD: Creates new paint every frame
        // using var paint = new SKPaint { Color = BackgroundColor.ToSKColor() };

        // ✅ GOOD: Reuse paint object
        _backgroundPaint ??= new SKPaint { IsAntialias = true };
        _backgroundPaint.Color = BackgroundColor.ToSKColor();

        canvas.DrawRoundRect(Bounds.ToSKRect(), CornerRadius, CornerRadius, _backgroundPaint);
    }

    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing)
    {
        if (disposing)
        {
            _backgroundPaint?.Dispose();
            _textPaint?.Dispose();
        }

        base.Dispose(disposing);
    }
}
```

## Image Resource Management

`SkiaImage` must carefully manage bitmap lifecycle:

```csharp
public class SkiaImage : SkiaView
{
    private SKBitmap? _bitmap;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _loadCts;

    protected override async void OnSourceChanged()
    {
        // Cancel any in-progress load
        _loadCts?.Cancel();
        _loadCts = new CancellationTokenSource();

        // Dispose old bitmap
        _bitmap?.Dispose();
        _bitmap = null;

        try
        {
            _bitmap = await LoadImageAsync(Source, _loadCts.Token);
            InvalidateMeasure();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Load was cancelled - this is expected
        }
    }

    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing)
    {
        if (disposing)
        {
            _loadCts?.Cancel();
            _loadCts?.Dispose();
            _bitmap?.Dispose();
        }

        base.Dispose(disposing);
    }
}
```

## Memory Profiling

Use dotnet-trace and dotnet-counters to monitor memory usage:

```bash
# Monitor GC statistics
dotnet-counters monitor --process-id <PID> \
  --counters System.Runtime[gen-0-gc-count,gen-1-gc-count,gen-2-gc-count,alloc-rate]

# Capture memory allocation trace
dotnet-trace collect --process-id <PID> --profile gc-collect
```

## Memory Budget Guidelines

For a typical OpenMaui application:

- **Base memory footprint**: 50-80MB (runtime + libraries)
- **Per-view overhead**: 1-5KB managed + 0-50KB native (if cached)
- **Image caching**: Limit to 100-200MB total
- **GC frequency**: <1 Gen 2 collection per minute during steady state
- **Allocation rate**: <1MB/sec during animations

Exceeding these budgets indicates memory leaks or inefficient resource management that will degrade performance over time.

## Profiling with BenchmarkDotNet and Custom Metrics

Effective performance optimization requires accurate measurement. OpenMaui's test suite includes comprehensive benchmarks using BenchmarkDotNet, plus custom instrumentation for real-time profiling.

## Setting Up BenchmarkDotNet

The OpenMaui codebase includes 217+ unit tests with performance benchmarks:

```csharp
using BenchmarkDotNet.Attributes;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Running;

[MemoryDiagnoser]
[SimpleJob(warmupCount: 3, iterationCount: 10)]
public class RenderingBenchmarks
{
    private SkiaLabel _label;
    private SKCanvas _canvas;
    private SKSurface _surface;

    [GlobalSetup]
    public void Setup()
    {
        _label = new SkiaLabel
        {
            Text = "Hello, World!",
            FontSize = 16,
            Width = 200,
            Height = 50
        };

        var info = new SKImageInfo(800, 600);
        _surface = SKSurface.Create(info);
        _canvas = _surface.Canvas;
    }

    [Benchmark]
    public void DrawLabel()
    {
        _canvas.Clear(SKColors.White);
        _label.Draw(_canvas);
        _canvas.Flush();
    }

    [Benchmark]
    public void DrawLabelWithCache()
    {
        _label.EnableRenderCache = true;
        _canvas.Clear(SKColors.White);
        _label.Draw(_canvas);
        _canvas.Flush();
    }

    [GlobalCleanup]
    public void Cleanup()
    {
        _label.Dispose();
        _surface.Dispose();
    }
}

// Run benchmarks
public class Program
{
    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        BenchmarkRunner.Run<RenderingBenchmarks>();
    }
}
```

## Typical Benchmark Results

```
|                Method |     Mean |    Error |   StdDev | Gen 0 | Allocated |
|---------------------- |---------:|---------:|---------:|------:|----------:|
|             DrawLabel | 1.234 ms | 0.045 ms | 0.038 ms |  3.90 |   16.2 KB |
|    DrawLabelWithCache | 0.156 ms | 0.008 ms | 0.007 ms |  0.49 |    2.1 KB |
```

This shows render caching reduces frame time by **87%** and allocations by **87%**.

## Custom Performance Instrumentation

Add custom metrics to your application:

```csharp
public class PerformanceMonitor
{
    private readonly Dictionary<string, PerformanceCounter> _counters = new();

    public class PerformanceCounter
    {
        public long TotalCalls { get; set; }
        public long TotalMilliseconds { get; set; }
        public long MinMilliseconds { get; set; } = long.MaxValue;
        public long MaxMilliseconds { get; set; }

        public double AverageMs => TotalCalls > 0 ? (double)TotalMilliseconds / TotalCalls : 0;
    }

    public IDisposable Measure(string operation)
    {
        return new PerformanceMeasurement(this, operation);
    }

    private class PerformanceMeasurement : IDisposable
    {
        private readonly PerformanceMonitor _monitor;
        private readonly string _operation;
        private readonly Stopwatch _stopwatch;

        public PerformanceMeasurement(PerformanceMonitor monitor, string operation)
        {
            _monitor = monitor;
            _operation = operation;
            _stopwatch = Stopwatch.StartNew();
        }

        public void Dispose()
        {
            _stopwatch.Stop();
            _monitor.RecordMeasurement(_operation, _stopwatch.ElapsedMilliseconds);
        }
    }

    private void RecordMeasurement(string operation, long milliseconds)
    {
        if (!_counters.TryGetValue(operation, out var counter))
        {
            counter = new PerformanceCounter();
            _counters[operation] = counter;
        }

        counter.TotalCalls++;
        counter.TotalMilliseconds += milliseconds;
        counter.MinMilliseconds = Math.Min(counter.MinMilliseconds, milliseconds);
        counter.MaxMilliseconds = Math.Max(counter.MaxMilliseconds, milliseconds);
    }

    public void PrintReport()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("\n=== Performance Report ===");
